# Start of question: behaviour of colliding waves
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:behaviour of colliding waves
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
What happens to two waves as they run into each other?
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
They pass through each other with the displacement of the medium being the sum of the displacements due to the individual waves.
:ANSWER2:0:H
They bounce off of each other.
:ANSWER3:0:H
They bounce off of each other and during the collision the displacement of the medium is the sum of the displacements due to the individual waves.
:ANSWER4:0:H
They pass through each other and the displacement of the medium is the displacement due to the larger wave.
:CAT:interference in 1-D
:Used By1:2870834344,3073873980,3183399116
:Used By3:3183399116,2870834344
# End of question: behaviour of colliding waves

# Start of question: interference from two speakers (in line)
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:interference from two speakers (in line)
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
Two speakers, which are good approximations of point sources, are on the x-axis.  They are playing the same steady tone, in phase with each other.  The speakers are separated by exactly half of a wavelength.  If you walk away from them along the x-axis what will you hear?
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
you won't hear the speakers at all because of destructive interference.
:ANSWER2:0:H
the sound from the speakers modulate between high pitch and low pitch as you move along the x-axis.
:ANSWER3:0:H
there will be as steady sound that is twice as loud as the sound from one speaker.
:ANSWER4:0:H
the sound from the speakers alternate between loud and silent as you move along the x-axis.
:CAT:interference in 1-D
:Used By1:3183399116
:Used By3:3183399116
# End of question: interference from two speakers (in line)

