# Start of question: Production of standing waves
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:Production of standing waves
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
Water waves with <FONT FACE="symbol">l</FONT> = 1.0 m, frequency 1.0 s<sup>-1</sup>, and amplitude, A = 20 cm traveling to the east run into waves with the same wavelength, frequency and amplitude moving to the west.  The result is
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
standing waves of amplitude 40 cm with nodes separated by 0.5 m.
:ANSWER2:0:H
standing waves of amplitude 40 cm with nodes separated by 1.0 m.
:ANSWER3:0:H
standing waves of amplitude 20 cm with nodes separated by 0.5 m.
:ANSWER4:0:H
a big confused mess as the waves interfere constructively in some places and destructively in other places.
:CAT:interference in 1-D
:Used By1:2870834344,3073873980,3183399116
:Used By3:3183399116,2870834344
# End of question: Production of standing waves

# Start of question: wavelengths of standing waves on a string
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:wavelengths of standing waves on a string
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
A string of length, L, is fixed (tied down) at both ends.  Possible lengths of standing waves on this string are\:
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
2L, L, 2L/3, L/4, 2L/5, ...
:ANSWER2:0:H
all wavelengths shorter than L
:ANSWER3:0:H
all wavelengths shorter than 2L
:ANSWER4:0:H
L, L/2, L/4, L/8, L/16, ...
:ANSWER5:0:H
L, L/2, L/3, L/4, L/5, ...
:CAT:interference in 1-D
:Used By1:2870834344,3073873980,3183399116
:Used By3:3183399116,2870834344
# End of question: wavelengths of standing waves on a string

