# Start of question: harmonics on a violin
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:harmonics on a violin
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
When the A string of a violin is played it produces a note at 440 Hz.  If you touch the middle of the string you force there to be a node there.  This changes the frequency of vibration of the string to
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
880 Hz
:ANSWER2:0:H
220 Hz
:ANSWER3:0:H
The frequency does not change, only the wavelength.
:ANSWER4:0:H
110 Hz
:CAT:interference in 1-D
:Used By1:2870834344,3073873980,3183399116
:Used By3:3183399116,2870834344
# End of question: harmonics on a violin

# Start of question: frequencies of harmonics of rope
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:frequencies of harmonics of rope
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
As you excite a rope to higher and higher harmonics the wavelengths of the standing waves on the rope become shorter and shorter.  What happens to the frequency of vibration?
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
The frequencies become higher as you exite higher harmonics.
:ANSWER2:0:H
The frequencies become lower as you exite higher harmonics.
:ANSWER3:0:H
The frequencies of all the harmonics are the same.
:ANSWER4:0:H
It depends on how you excite the harmonics.
:CAT:interference in 1-D
:Used By1:2870834344,3073873980,3183399116
:Used By3:3183399116,2870834344
# End of question: frequencies of harmonics of rope

